Data Set¶

The dataset contains 1000 cases of customers who received credit from German banks.
For each customer, relevant financial and personal information was recorded.
Whether a customer repaid or defaulted on the loan was also recorded in the "Credit" column. 300 of the 1000 customers failed to repay (Credit=2).

The 20 attributes and output variable are described in the file Resources/Data/GermanCredit/credit_metadata.txt
There are 13 qualitative and 7 numerical attributes. Each attribute has a descriptive name.
The values of qualitative (categorical) attributes are codes. The meaning of each code is listed in the metadata file.

Problem¶

Propose an optimal classification model that forecasts credit risk (good/bad credit outcome) given the above attributes.
You can use any of the ML algorithms and metrics we have discussed in class.
The optimal model must be better than at least one alternative model.

Minimum requirements¶

  • Basic exploratory data analysis (EDA)
  • Construction of at least two binary classification models to select from
  • Metrics-based arguments about model selection and parameter tuning
  • If you use other people's work or ideas, add references at the end

In [154]:
metadata_path = '/Users/jili/OneDrive - nyu.edu/7773/Data/GermanCredit/credit_metadata.txt'
metadata = []
with open(metadata_path, 'r') as f:
    flag = 0
    attr_index = 1
    Attr_flag = 0
    for line in f:
        if line == '\n':
            Attr_flag = 0
        if Attr_flag == 1:
            parse = line.find(':')
            n_place = line.find('\n')
            metadata[attr_index-2]['class'][line[:parse-1]] = line[parse+1: n_place-1]
        if flag != 0:
            flag = 0
            n_place = line.find('\n')
            metadata[attr_index-2]['name'] = line[:n_place-1]
            if metadata[attr_index-2]['type'] == 'qualitative':
                Attr_flag = 1
            metadata[attr_index-2]['class'] = {}
        if 'Attribute ' + str(attr_index) in line:
            Attr_flag = 0
            flag = 1
            metadata.append({})
            metadata[attr_index-1]['type'] = 'numerical' if 'numerical' in line else 'qualitative'          
            attr_index += 1

GermanCredit.rename(columns = dict(zip(GermanCredit.columns,[attr['name']for attr in metadata])), inplace=True)

In [155]:
all_cat_cols = [attr['name'] \
                for attr in metadata \
                if attr['type'] == 'qualitative' ]
all_num_cols = [attr['name'] \
                for attr in metadata \
                if attr['type'] == 'numerical' ]
encoded_attr_list = []
for col in all_cat_cols:
    return_obj = mlutils.fit_transform_ohe(GermanCredit, col)
    encoded_attr_list.append({'label_enc': return_obj[0],
                              'ohe_enc': return_obj[1],
                              'feature_df': return_obj[2],
                              'col_name': col})
    
feature_df_list = [GermanCredit[all_num_cols]]
feature_df_list.extend([enc['feature_df'] \
                        for enc in encoded_attr_list ])
df = pd.concat(feature_df_list, axis=1)

# Give better name to each column
new_col_names = []
for new_name in df.columns:
    if '_' in new_name:
        parse = new_name.find('_')
        name = new_name[:parse]
        clss = [attr['class'][new_name[parse+1:]] for attr in metadata if attr['name'] == name][0]
        new_col_names.append(name+':'+clss)
df.columns = all_num_cols+new_col_names

df['credit'] = np.where(GermanCredit.Credit.values==2, 0, 1)

1.The first plot shows that most of the customers are single young male and divorced/separated/married young female.(absence of data for single women)

2.It also shows that single old male and divorced/separated/married old female can repay the loan. But when a young male or a young divorced/separated/married young female has a large amount of credits, the probabilities of default are much higher than other cases.

3.The second plot shows most loans are sought to buy new car,furniture/equipment.

4.It also reveals that most people buying used cars can repay the money most of time. And not surprisingly, customers with lower age and higher loan amount are the main source of bad credits.

5.The third plot shows most loans are in 3 years. And not surprisingly, with the increasing of duration in years, the credit amount also has a upgoing trend. It also tells us loans with duration less than or equal to 2 years are less likely to default.

Metrics Function¶

In [112]:
def Classifer_Metrics(libcls, X_test, y_test):
    y_pred = libcls.predict(X_test)
    confmat = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    conf_df = pd.DataFrame(confmat, index = ['bad', 'good'], columns = ['bad', 'good'])
    conf_df.index.names = ['act\pred']
    display(conf_df)
    
    
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    prec = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    rec = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    #print(acc, prec, rec, f1)
    metric = pd.DataFrame({'accuracy': acc, 'precision': prec, 'recall': rec, 'F1 score': f1}, index=['metrics'])
    #display(metric)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 4))
    grid = plt.GridSpec(1, 3)
    plt.subplot(grid[0:1])
    sn.set()
    sn.barplot( data=metric)
    
    y_pred_prob = libcls.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

    # compute ROC and AUC
    fpr, tpr, thr = roc_curve(y_test,  y_pred_prob)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)

    # plot ROC
    plt.subplot(grid[1:3])
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr)
    plt.title("ROC with AUC={0:3.2f}".format(auc))
    plt.xlabel('FPR')
    plt.ylabel('TPR')

Oversampling¶

We use SMOTE to generate more data for the minority class. The point is we must do oversampling after splitting the original dataset. Otherwise the training set may contain some samples generated by SMOTE and similar to samples in the training set.

In [114]:

Random Forest¶

Intuitively, predicting bad as good is worse than the opposite. This is mainly because it would cause more loss for the bank. So, we set class_weight to be {0:5,1:1}, which means we assign larger weights to bad class.

In [124]:
rnd_clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=rnd, class_weight={0:5,1:1}, 
                                 min_samples_leaf = 1, max_depth=11, oob_score = True)
rnd_clf.fit(X_train_os, y_train_os)

We mainly tune three hyperparameters min_samples_leaf,max_features and max_depth. We select best hyperparameters based on roc_auc score on testset by grid search with cross validation.
